We'd like to thank all patients, clinicians and scientists involved in collecting the samples and generating the data, as well as @pathogenomenick and @Scalene for their great advice!
All generated data are publicly and openly (no strings attached) available via GenBank / SRA, as well as via @GISAID.  You can also find the samples on @nextstrain.

Interestingly, we observe evidence for multi-allelic variant positions in a quite a few samples. These may represent infections with more than one strain. More data needed. In any case, other people have noticed, too: https://t.co/HvAPxlK2MN

We also include some interesting technical data, such as a @nanopore / @illumina comparison on 12 samples (they are in very good agreement) and some results on direct cDNA sequencing, after having primed the reverse transcription with @NetworkArtic primers.

The original source of the Heinsberg outbreak remains ambiguous - there is a travel history of the first two patients to the Netherlands consistent with reported incubation times, but there's only very limited circulation of the Heinsberg strain in NL, despite deep sampling.

Intriguingly, we did not observe widespread circulation of Heinsberg-type strains in D√ºsseldorf despite geographical proximity. This may reflect that contact tracing and containment efforts worked to some extent, but more data needed.

The genetic data are consistent with classical epidemiology: while the Heinsberg viral isolates form a clonal clade, many different strains are circulating in D√ºsseldorf, likely reflecting multiple introduction events, e.g. via air travel (Germany's third-largest airport).

Our analysis includes samples from the "Heinsberg Outbreak" (Germany's first large-scale SARS-CoV-2 outbreak and driven by superspreading dynamics during a carnival session), as well as from nearby D√ºsseldorf (70km away). Sequencing based on @NetworkArtic protocol and @nanopore.

This ensures your code is always kept in a working state. As you 'enable' the change you still know what your code should be doing. Only in the last step do you actually change the functionality of the code.

In programming, this means first changing your code to allow for a certain change without changing any of the existing functionality (/output).Get it to a point where making the change is obviously simple, and then make the actual change.
"Enable the change before you make the change" ‚Äì is one of the most artful pieces of engineering advice I've received.

I worry scientific populism is nearly as damaging to our ability to deal with #COVID19 than ‚Äòseverity denialism‚Äô. It will also fuel further anger and resentment in society when the empty promises will die. Then, I don't know how to fight this form of disinformation.(4/4)

The typical manifestation of #COVID19 scientific populism is a mix of sloganeering, foolish optimism, a can-do attitude, complete disregard for facts, a dose of righteousness and a propensity to blame anyone who doesn't buy in the latest in vogue delusion.(3/4)

The blatant untruths are easy to counter. What I hadn't anticipated and I struggle with is 'scientific populism'. This is largely fuelled by a few academics with no prior experience in infectious disease epidemiology, who have established themselves as COVID19 'experts'.(2/4)

It's been now slightly over two months that I decided to dedicate some of my time to inform the public on #COVID19 and try to fight disinformation. It feels like a Sisyphean task at times as the nonsense is coming so hard and fast from all sides.(1/4)

5) The mystery persists.  How does a cancer develop, with no obvious gene-specific defect?

4) Eric has observed that most ileal NETs are multifocal, suggesting multiple independent clones. And Zhouwei found that the lost chromosome 18 could be either from the mother or the father, in these multifocal NETs. So an underlying germline mutation on chromosome 18 is unlikely

3) One idea about chromosome 18 LOH is that there is a germline mutation that is then complemented by loss of the wild-type allele.  We studied multifocal ileal NETs identified by our colleague, surgeon Dr. Eric Nakakura at UCSF.

2) Ileal NETs are unusual in that no driver mutation can be found in most cases.  Loss of function mutations in the cyclin dependent kinase inhibitor CDKN1B are found in ~10% of cases. And chromosome 18 LOH is found in most cases.

In addition to CSE, I also recommend the American Medical Writer's Association (AMWA), if you are interested in writing publications on clinical trials. AMWA offers numerous online coursework as well. (+)

I did freelance scientific editing/writing for 12 years before making the transition back to an in-house job, first in industry and then in academia. The connections that I made through clients as a freelancer have been invaluable, as have the research skills I've learned. (+)

If your postodoc or faculty job didn't work out (or you are worried it won't) - this is a great avenue to have "something on the side" that brings in extra revenue as a scientific back-up option. It keeps your mind on the science, so you can transition back to the lab later. (+)

PIs are writing a LOT right now, and they are desperate for scientific editors. I have had 3 of my former clients contact me in the last month. I can't take them because I have my own full-time job. IF YOU WANT TO BE A SCIENTIFIC EDITOR, NOW IS THE TIME TO DO IT! (+)

You can work part-time - if you DO get a job, it's easy to stop. There's also the possibility to have it be your full-time job (but, it IS gig work - so it's not stable, which is why I left). Best of all, the work is global - you aren't dependent on US economy. (+)

Tetraploids have gone through more intense breeding/selection for a longer time to produce larger tubers and to be able to self-pollinate. It isn't necessarily a consequence of them being tetraploid.

A side effect of that decision is the tubers I grow are likely to be smaller than usual. As well, the diploids aren't able to self-pollinate. I need to plant 2+ varieties at once if I want seeds for the next year.

I decided to work with #DiploidPotato instead of the usual tetraploids because it would be easier to observe genetics ratios and to make predictions about what I might get in each generation. https://t.co/QxDcFWok8p

All of this is to say what probably everyone I'm connected to on here is probably already in agreement on, but...Immigrants are key members of our society at EVERY level!I know none of these insights are novel, but sometimes I just need to scream into the void.

Since becoming a scientist I've also seen the opposite side of this spectrum. I began working in labs as an undergrad and I've had the opportunity to work with immigrants from every continent. These folks have been mentors, advisors, friends, collaborators, and trainees.

Because of this family story - and because I grew up somewhere that had a lack of immigrants -  I grew up with the idea of immigration being tied to hard manual labor jobs. It is certainly true that immigrants do make up many of these workers particular in certain sectors. But...

Most of them landed in Butte Montana (the largest city between Chicago and SF at the time) working in the various mines. These were hard jobs, but numerous immigrants from around the word flocked to Butte to work. The rest of my family were homesteaders.

Most of my family immigrated to the US *fairly* recently - great great grandparents. Roughly 3/4 of my family were Irish and 1/4 slavic. Their stories of immigration were a cornerstone of my childhood. All of them immigrated to Montana and lived hard lives

There are of course, gray zones too, which require discussion between physician and patient.  And there are also opportunities for learning what is essential and what is not. That's part of the ongoing journey of medicine and evidence-based practice.

In other cases, not having the lab result could pose a greater danger to the patient's health, for example patients who are on warfarin, a blood thinner, need to have their blood checked to make sure they are not on too high or too low of a dose.

We recognize that going into a lab to get blood drawn is a potential risk (labs have set up protocols to minimize this risk). If the lab test is not vital and could be delayed for 1-2 months without significant consequence (example: checking Hgb A1c), then the lab may be delayed.

"Did I really need those labs?" Patients are wondering if they "really" needed labs/blood draws that have now been postponed due to #COVID19.  The answer: it depends. Physicians make decisions about an intervention based on benefit versus risk.

Home labs + satellite lab rooms where dift labs can interact. These rooms will be able to allow individuals to come in faster than giant, hall-like open lab spaces.
Requires sharing between labs, pooling of resources, which can be tough to convince people to do.

I "grew up" in the Stanford Biochem dpt, in the Beckman bldg- perfect mix of small rooms (4-6 people), shared equipment rooms (to minimize replication), and shared stock room. Had no idea until later how rare this ideal lab set up was.
I can see how open labs were an administrator's dream, and in the very few, very best cases actually did lead to some interactions. But ignored many realities of both science and how people function.

I‚Äôve wanted to develop a file system scavenger hunt exercise to help students understand their file sys but have never done it 9/

Many students new to #rstats struggle with understanding their computers file system.  Using rstudio cloud helps, or a teaching package .  Directly loading or scraping data from online sources is easy too  8/
A popular exercise is to have students build ugly graphs in #rstats.      Could be a good team project for when classes move online.  I know @gabbspalomo had some awesome submissions this spring 7/

I‚Äôve been reminded that when teaching intro  #rstats dataviz helps keep students engaged  I really like teAching ggplot using ggpubr as a starting point.  This could be really important when courses move online 6/. H/t @BrandonHoenig

For moving #rstats courses online I‚Äôm considering building Multiple choice and fill in the blanks exercises in our Learning management software @CanvasLMS student will get a script then answer questions & annotate code and enter answers into online assignment 6/

My biggest worry for moving intro #rstats courses online is helping students learn to spot errors eg missing commas.  I think I am going to develop ‚Äúpin the comma on the broken script‚Äù type exercises. Missing , ( [ and = in arguments really grind new users down 5/
Rstudio offers free cloud hosting for learnr and shiny  but there are caps on users, which won‚Äôt work for larger classes 4/

Outside of rstudio cloud the learnr ecosystem doesn‚Äôt seem to be too developed but the platform is really cool, though labor intensive to build. Can be hosted on cloud or embedded into a package üì¶ 3/

If you think you might benefit from this kind of support while navigating what are by all accounts precarious and taxing circumstances, I highly recommend it. 6/6(And +1 for quarantine car therapy. I recommend that as well).

Academia is replete with uncertainty and opportunity for self-doubt. There are conflicting messages about how to achieve success and what success even looks like. Many of us make large personal sacrifices as we work towards uncertain professional goals. 5/6

For me, this has inspired a willingness to take significant (to me) risks and to tolerate the prospect of failure in order to do work that I find important, meaningful, and fulfilling. I am a better scientist, colleague, and human for it. 4/6

But it can also serve as a space (and an excuse) to clarify personal and professional goals, identify barriers to achieving them, and take steps towards them, with the knowledge that you have a consistent source of support if things don't go as planned. 3/6

It has been, without a doubt, the most powerful, productive, and transformative experience of my life. We (myself included) tend to think of therapy as a space to work through defined challenges, major life events, etc. 2/6

The result is that society is tearing itself apart, and Facebook has played a big role in that before now. Unfortunately though, the only conclusion we can arrive at based on the outcry today is that the Backfire Effect is real. 4/4

However, sadly Facebook's actions indicate that we have reached a point where things have gotten so bad that Facebook feels a moral obligation to intervene. We are not collectively doing a good enough job researching truth ourselves, or thinking critically about what is true. 3/4
We shouldn't be looking to viral Facebook posts as our main source of truth. It's certainly not Facebook's job to determine what is true, and that's why they're punting to fact checker sites. 2/4

Since all I see on Facebook today seem to be posts about people complaining about Facebook "censoring" posts (by directing people to fact checkers), I want to add a contrasting view. I'm glad Facebook is doing something to clean up the backwater that social media has become. 1/4

I wouldn't fully rule out that the relatively complacent initial response by some governments to #COVID19 might marginally have had something to do with scientific advisors being worried of coming across as systematically 'overreacting' to outbreaks/epidemics.(3/5)'

What these social distancing policies are and when exactly they started is the info we need to enable better evidence-based decision making about how phase out social distancing in a safe and responsible fashion. Help us track them down at https://t.co/WBFu5OZ8Yj!

The reason we don't have this data is that a large portion of social distancing policy was enacted at the county and city level.So there are thousands of different policies that apply in different regions of the US, that each took effect at different times.

For example, scientists know that Texas is planning to phase out social distancing much too quickly, with dangerous consequences. But they can't predict what the magnitude of the risk is as accurately as they could if they had better data.https://t.co/1tlJm6Hc7k

But that graph tells something else: the probability that a person in each age range *who has covid-19* will die of it. The distribution of covid-19 deaths across ages is obtained by multiplying these case fatality rates by the fraction of population in each age range.    /2

@eskay8 Sorry, I don't think I understand what you are saying

Coronaviruses replicate in ~10 h. Thus, if an infection started with ~100 virions, they would be a mighty ~3,200 after 2.5 days. This is far from an 'infection', and a patient carrying ~3,200 viruses would hardly be infective, i.e. most aerosolised virions fail to transmit. (5/5)

For their model to fit, the authors have to force an extraordinarily fast epidemic doubling time of ~2.5 days. This falls at the lower end of the incubation period for #COVID19 and feels implausible for some other reasons (4/5).

The authors do not consider the #COVID19 epidemic in the US started before mid-January, fine. Though, they seem to  observe an excess in Flu-Like Symptoms (eFLSs) often peaking in 2019 already. I found no attempt in the paper to explain the earlier non-COVID19 eFLSs. (3/5) https://t.co/UcFFEm8XNe

The work builds on the assumption that any excess in reported Flu-Like Symptoms must be due to COVID. This is in itself problematic as unmonitored epidemics of all sorts of viruses, bacteria and mycoplasma causing mild flu-like symptoms happen all the time. (2/5)

This preprint has been around a while https://t.co/bYj0uERk7T. Now that it's been picked by the media, it can't be ignored anymore. The modelling is quite sophisticated but some of the assumptions and interpretations are questionable, to say the least. (1/5) https://t.co/TRitjfn0as

If you believe that a movie isn't worth evaluating fairly, just be honest about it. Of course, that won't get the clicks, however.

IOW, put actual effort into making sense of the thing, then evaluate how much of that effort is reasonable against the artistic merit of the piece. What's really being said when step 1 is skipped: "My prejudice says that no amount of effort is reasonable in this case."

"What is this film trying to achieve (with every benefit of the doubt), is it successful in its attempt and is it worth achieving?" are the right questions, not "Let's assume that this film is an incoherent and superficial mess and interpret it through that lens".

"Sure, it makes sense if you assume X, but the filmmaker would never be that smart" is the laziest bit of film criticism possible. Approach the film in good faith, on its terms, then discuss why you think it's (un)successful in its goals, or why those goals have little worth.

And if you know JGI, you already guessed the next step.. "What if we searched every (meta)genome we have ?". So we first figured out how to systematically detect DGRs, then we mined public (meta)genomes, and went from the ~1,500 DGRs currently identified to > 30,000 (!)

Collectively, we had (as of 2019) about ~ 1,500 different DGR sequences identified, however it is still unclear exactly who is using these systems in nature and for what ? Is this mostly viruses ? cells ? Is it always used in virus:host interactions like the original DGR ?

Now we have known about DGR existence for ~ 2 decades, and in the last few years several studies (most led by @gnome_science) also detected sequences that looked like DGRs in metagenomeshttps://t.co/jEeRjpYku2https://t.co/JgT49IZ2YJ

It's too complex to give it justice here, but suffice to say it involves an error-prone reverse-transcriptase, some imperfect repeat, plus some stem-loop, plus other things we have not characterized yet

The mechanism itself is really interesting from a molecular side, and has been very well described elsewhere e.g. https://t.co/NvTUgbw2N5 or https://t.co/iDdKlg65kZ

More generally, DGRs are kind of like cheating at the (evolutionary) slot machine: instead of spinning everything at every round, you keep everything in place (e.g. the two 7s you already have), and only spin the one symbol you want to. https://t.co/KWuFjrx4AN

In the first instance ever described, a DGR in a phage genome was used to introduce mutation in a gene involved in host recognition, i.e. if the host changed, the phage can quickly adapt (while keeping the rest of its genome intact).
First discovered in a phage (of course), in 2002, DGRs are systems that microbes and viruses use to get (a lot of) mutations *in one place and in one place only*. https://t.co/BfQTJdXFMl

This without even considering how to extract uncertainty estimates for the network, which is hard even when casting as a continuous problem. Hardest when the network becomes a non-parametric model like at the end of the blog post

For example, learning weights of gene/protein interactions given some omics data to prioritize genes to look at downstream. The function of gene network -> gene list is likely more important than the network estimation itself, and may not even rely on the full network structure.

Of note, one of the unsolved challenges in this area is yielding interpretable statistical objects with proper uncertainty estimates. A weighted graph with edge uncertainties is a bulky abstraction when trying to distill it to actionable insights in a given domain.

The second cluster of SARS-Cov-2 genomes we sequenced are related to genomes sampled mostly in the Washington state.This pattern evidences that coast-to-coast transmissions are taking place in the US.See our preprint for more details: https://t.co/MFZeGPgQSN https://t.co/6cZ2yuT6FE

The SARS-CoV-2 genomes we sequenced are grouped in two main clusters (clades), based on genetic similarity.The first clade shows mainly genomes sampled in New York state, Canada and Western Europe, and reveal local transmissions between CT and NY. https://t.co/wzW5Gnouyx

Seven major cholera pandemics between 1817-1975, causing tenths, if not hundreds of millions of deaths. To give you an idea of the scale of devastation, during the third cholera pandemic (1846-1860), 5.5% of the population of Chicago died within a single year. (3/4) https://t.co/8IengtMm5f

Cocoliztli (Great pestilence), 12 major (and many minor) epidemics in 'New Spain' causing millions of deaths in the 16th-18th century, possibly caused by Salmonella enterica serovar typhi. Most likely pandemics but evidence outside the Americas sketchy. (2/4) https://t.co/XG2L36jrqU

Though, I personally believe, as callous and cynical as this may sound, that once #COVID19 got out of control, several countries have implemented (possibly more by accident than design) strategies not that far off from what might be considered as epidemiologically sensible. (6/6)

Politically, the handling of the #COVID19 pandemic could be considered as an embarrassment for many countries. The general lack of foresight and decisiveness in the early stages of the outbreak, as well as the, at times, borderline obfuscation could be rightly criticised. (5/6)

We got caught out napping and any serious response in the West only got implemented after there was sustained, widespread transmission of #COVId19. This greatly limited our options, and there was no real alternative to lockdowns at this stage. (4/6)

There was a window of opportunity earlier in the #COVID19 pandemic, where it could have been controlled. We missed it, for various reasons, ranging from lack of preparedness to complacency. We should analyse our failings in the future, but now is not the time for blame. (3/6)

As concerns the best 'way out', I'm afraid, I personally, cannot see any viable alternative to ensuring immunity builds up in the population, through infection or vaccination. What is critical is to minimise hospital overload, to ensure mortality is kept as low as possible. (2/6)

We provide a #PAH-specific #GRN for pulmonary arterial endothelial cells - let us know if you are interested in using it

My take-homes for this study: 1) #chromatin can capture a cell's regulatory state better than RNA 2) #chromatin changes best interpreted as #TF activity in the context of a  #GRN 3)  #enhancers prime pulmonary arterial endothelial cells in #PAH to aberrant response

The changes in the #GRN converge on endothelial to mesenchymal transition and response to signaling. Follow-up experiments confirmed that genes with differential H3K27ac in enhancers show differential expression when treated with endogenous stimuli (no difference at baseline)

The most striking part of this study was the absence of detectable difference in RNA expression, yet huge changes in H3K27ac marks, which recapitulated differential activity in almost all known #PAH TFs and suggested a complete rewiring of the gene regulatory network (#GRN).

#multiomics in #PAH patients: remodeling of gene regulatory network (#GRN) primes pulmonary arterial endothelial cells to aberrant signaling response leading to proliferation and EndMT. @armandorp collaboration Marlene Rabinovitch & @SnyderShot @StanfordMed @embl @LiSciAlliance https://t.co/QYuMoU9LwC
